reviewText: Got this for my kids to get them in the Christmas mood, but it was a waste. Like the fact that they go through popular Christmas songs that kids should know, and that the words are displayed at the bottom of the screen in a sing-a-long so they can follow along. And the scenes are taken from popular Disney classics so kids can watch the clips along with the music video. BUT the whole set-up of this DVD is very cheesy, not executed very well. They constantly show images of a model christmas village, and I often forgot i was watching a Disney DVD! I think if it were all cartoon it would be more enjoyable. Just thought this was boring, and my kids actually asked me to turn it off because of that! Waste of money personally!

reviewText: When this video came out, I was working at the Disney Store and our jumbo screen played the video clips on it over and over. I didn't think about it then, but in hindsight I realize that the Disney Company doesn't make videos like this anymore! (Can you imagine ~ Joy to the world!) I'm an active Christian and look for videos and music that include traditional Christmas carols. Now that I have a family of my own, I'm thrilled that my kids can sing along with this video some of the songs we sing in church every year. It's also fun to see some of the older Disney shorts that bring back so many great childhood memories. We've worn it out so much that I'm buying a new one to replace it! Truly a gem in our holiday collection.
summary: A favorite video for a Christian family

reviewText: In the 1980s Disney released Disney's Sing Along Songs: Very Merry Christmas Songs on VHS. This program featured Christmas songs with scenes from Disney cartoons on screen along with the words, often highlighted by a Mickey Mouse head. It lasted 30 minutes and had the following songs- Deck The Halls, Up On The Housetop, Joy To The World, Let It Snow, Sleigh Ride, Winter Wonderland, Here Comes Santa Claus (At Disneyland), Rudolph The Red Nosed Reindeer, Jingle Bells, Silent Night and We Wish You A Merry Christmas.In 2002, Disney released Disney's Sing Along Songs: Very Merry Christmas Songs on DVD. Unlike what the ... Editorial Review states, this version lasts 54 minutes, and not just 30 minutes. This new DVD edition features the same songs from the VHS version, along with some additions. These include- a new version of Jingle Bells, Toyland, All I Want For Christmas Is My Two Front Teeth, The Best Christmas Of All, White Christmas, Rockin' Around The Christmas Tree, Jingle Bell Rock, As Long As There's A Christmas and Seasons Of Giving.This program on DVD is just great for the children just as it was on VHS so I do recommend it. The special features which include a Words Of The Season Vocabulary Game, a Very Merry Musical Game and Create-A-Card Activity are also great fun for the children and very appropriate for this kind of DVD.Buy Disney's Sing Along Songs: A Very Merry Christmas and have a very merry Christmas!!
summary: The NEW Very Merry Christmas Songs

reviewText: Nobody likes the old stuff and nostalgia as much as I do.  I had this in VHS and wanted to replace it.  This DVD has even more songs on it than the VHS version did.  The illustrations are wonderful, and the way they match the music (like in Fantasia) is great!  I had borrowed the DVD from my son when he was moving, but when I tried to play it, it was cracked.  So when I bought one to replace his, I bought one for myself too!  I heard some traditional songs for the holidays (my era and older) and then some newer songs from Beauty and the Beast.  It is a great mood elevator and the children will be glued by the animation.  You won't be sorry!Disney's Sing Along Songs - Very Merry Christmas Songs

reviewText: True, the VHS version of Sing Along Songs: Very Merry Christmas Songs is pure Disney woven classic with no undue narration between musical scenes, unlike the DVD copy with additional Disney scenes I can also appreciate. Your best bet is get both, yes both versions for your home entertainment library, because both are just as good in their own specific way. I like the additional Winnie The Pooh songs in the DVD copy not included on VHS version, but the VHS has the unmistakable opening of Jimney Cricket beginning the show as most Disney purists can appreciate with his "From All Of Us, To All Of You" song accompanied by Mickey Mouse on piano, which DVD does not include. Also the fireworks Christmas greeting at the end of VHS one.Best bet is to have both copies because you can never have too much Disney Christmas cheer!
summary: Dont crucify the DVD this holiday season

reviewText: The one star reviews are dissatisfied with this DVD because it's not the same as the old VHS version. However, if you don't compare the two, this DVD is very enjoyable. It lists on the back cover which songs are new to this version, and you'll be able to tell by the difference in animation. I love the classics best, but there's nothing wrong with the new cartoons. Many of the new cartoons come from Mickey's Once Upon a Christmas, Winnie the Pooh and one from Belle's Enchanted Christmas. My princess loving 3 yr old was glad for Belle's song.The narrator has been described as scary or creepy, but I disagree. It's actually the same narrator as the one in Babe. He reminds me of the classic Pooh narrators. I understand the reaction of those who hate the changes because they loved the old one so much. I hate it when they mess with things I loved too. But for everyone who has not seen the VHS version, there is no reason to not like this version!  All the old Disney cartoons are here, although I don't know if the singing is the same. But the singing was fine. The end song looks like it's from the House of Mouse cartoon. My nieces were glad to see all the Disney characters together in that one.There are only 2 religious songs if you're concerned about that. My nieces are Jewish so we just fast forward through the two Christian songs. But I'm glad they were included as I will love watching them with my own kids. Those two songs look like the cartoons are from Fantasia, so we aren't missing the Disney characters in them.
